    id: 42,
    cat: "ai",
    title: "You won&#8217;t have long to get these iPad deals before Apple&#8217;s price hike",
    summary: "Apple just raised prices across its iPad and MacBook lineup. The good news is that many retailers are still selling their inventory at the old prices or far less, which means you can still score some of the best iPad deals we may see in awhile — if ever again. So if you&#8217;ve been thinking [&#8230;]",
    body: "You can save hundreds on the latest iPad Air. | Photo by Amelia Holowaty Krales / The Verge Apple just raised prices across its iPad and MacBook lineup . The good news is that many retailers are still selling their inventory at the old prices or far less, which means you can still score some of the best iPad deals we may see in awhile — if ever again. So if you&#8217;ve been thinking about picking up a new iPad, now is probably the time to do it.\n\nNow the bad news: those discounts are starting to disappear, though. One of the best iPad deals of Prime Day, for instance, saw the M4-powered iPad Air with Wi-Fi and 128GB of storage drop to a record low of $519 when the sale kicked off. Amazon is still offering it for $519, which is $230 less than Apple&#8217;s new list price. Apple iPad Air M4 The M4-powered iPad Air offers 12GB of RAM, Apple Intelligence features, Apple Pencil Pro support, and Wi-Fi 7 and Bluetooth 6, making it a great middle ground between the entry-level iPad and iPad Pro.\n\nRead our review. Where to Buy: $749 $519.99 at Amazon (128GB, Wi-Fi) Compared to Apple&#8217;s entry-level iPad, the Air offers a faster M4 chip, 12GB of RAM, Apple Intelligence features, Apple Pencil Pro support. It also offers newer connectivity standards like Wi-Fi 7 and Bluetooth 6, making it a more future-proof option. If the iPad Air isn&#8217;t what you&#8217;re after, though, don&#8217;t worry.\n\nThere are still plenty of other iPad deals worth considering, whether you&#8217;re shopping for Apple&#8217;s affordable entry-level model or its high-end iPad Pro. Here are the best discounts we could find. iPad deals iPad (2025) Apple’s entry-level iPad is an excellent tablet for casual use, even if it is getting a little long in the tooth. Its high-res screen is great for watching video, and its A16 processor is still fast enough to handle light games and productivity apps.\n\nRead our review . Where to Buy: $449 $299 at Amazon (128GB, Wi-Fi) $449 $299 at Walmart (128GB, Wi-Fi) iPad Mini (2024) The iPad Mini’s smaller size is tailor-made for travel, with a light, sturdy design that’s easy to slip into a carry-on. Its compact 8.3-inch display is great for reading, watching movies, and playing games, and it even supports the Apple Pencil Pro, making it an excellent tool for doodling.\n\nThe battery holds up well, too, and you can easily pair it with a Bluetooth keyboard to tackle some light work. Read our review. Where to Buy: $699 $499.99 at Amazon (256GB, Wi-Fi) $599 $499.99 at Target (128GB, Wi-Fi) iPad Pro (2025) Apple’s newest iPad Pros have an M5 processor, an N1 chip, and a C1X chip for cellular versions. They’re faster, support Wi-Fi 7, charge more quickly, and start with 12GB of RAM.\n\nRead our review. Where to Buy: $1199 $937.76 at Amazon (11-inch, 256GB) $1399 $1099.99 at Amazon (11-inch, 512GB) $1299 $1199.99 at Amazon (13-inch, 256GB) Update, June 26th: Updated pricing and availability.",
    source: "The Verge",
